snippet.textDisplay: The hexagons of the cage are not true hexagons; bending them into a cylinder deforms them so that they're narrower than they ought to be, compared to hexagons on a flat surface.  The piece that needs to escape is a truncated octahedron, that normally has a regular hexagon as its profile.  This puzzle's octahedron deliberately has one profile wider than the other, which as you deduced, is part of the challenge: find the odd key to fit the odd lock, despite all keys and all locks seeming to be uniform.
snippet.textOriginal: The hexagons of the cage are not true hexagons; bending them into a cylinder deforms them so that they're narrower than they ought to be, compared to hexagons on a flat surface.
